00:04:52.150 --> 00:04:53.150
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: Very nice.

00:04:53.150 --> 00:04:55.580
It has a nice UI.

00:04:55.580 --> 00:04:59.080
Fairly straight forward using an action bar,
it's not actually an action bar it's more

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:01.380
of a pseudo action bar but, you know, that's
okay.

00:05:01.380 --> 00:05:04.650
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: You know we're seeing a lot
of this, Reto; we're seeing a lot of fake

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:06.410
action bars, why do you think that is?

00:05:06.410 --> 00:05:09.900
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: Probably because there's no
framework way of being able to have action

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:13.900
bars for devices running new, old versions
of Android.

00:05:13.900 --> 00:05:15.920
[Inaudible due to audio]

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:19.610
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: I think the,
[Cannot understand due to audio]

00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:26.300
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: It does provide something that
is very authentic and gives you that ability.

00:05:26.300 --> 00:05:30.360
With that said, I think what's happening in
this app, here, is totally legitimate.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:35.230
It is an, it is an action bar, it works the
way that you would expect it to.

00:05:35.230 --> 00:05:40.020
The only feedback I'd give in this particular
instance is to be careful about the icons,

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:42.010
the style of the icons that you're using.

00:05:42.010 --> 00:05:43.010
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Right.

00:05:43.010 --> 00:05:48.340
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: So, in this case they're using,
sort of, the themed icons so that they, sort

00:05:48.340 --> 00:05:50.680
of, faded into the action bar itself.

00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:54.880
It's an interesting approach but that's immediately
what makes it obvious that this isn't, you

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:56.160
know, a standard action bar.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:06:01.170
I would have a look at the design side and
stick to the design guidelines in terms of

00:06:01.170 --> 00:06:02.170
your icons.

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:03.170
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Right.

00:06:03.170 --> 00:06:07.550
This is, I think, what we've said over and
over is that if you have a great design idea

00:06:07.550 --> 00:06:10.760
that doesn't fit into our design guidelines,
by all means use it.

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:15.900
But, if you're trying to mimic something that
the Android design guidelines already covered

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:21.910
and it looks enough like a standard Android
feature that people might think it is then

00:06:21.910 --> 00:06:26.140
don't make it work differently and preferably
don't make it look particularly different.

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:27.140
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: Exactly.

00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:28.140
I think that's the key here.

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:32.130
If you wanna do something radically different
then that's a fantastic idea, I mean, we love

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:33.210
to see really innovative designs.

00:06:33.210 --> 00:06:38.400
But if you're doing something which is supposed
to, which looks like an action bar or any

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:42.910
other sort of system element, it should behave
the same way and it should look as close to

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:45.370
it as possible so you're not, sort of, getting
thrown.

00:06:45.370 --> 00:06:46.370
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Right.

00:06:46.370 --> 00:06:50.150
Now, speaking of icons, I think that's actually
my biggest concern about this app because

00:06:50.150 --> 00:06:52.170
I should say right off the top, I love this
app.

00:06:52.170 --> 00:06:53.170
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: It's a great app.

00:06:53.170 --> 00:06:58.040
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: I love the fact that this
app exists, I love the idea behind it but

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:03.540
there is one thing that I am concerned about
and that is that the app is using these icons

00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:05.590
which represent each of the applications.

00:07:05.590 --> 00:07:11.960
Now, those applications have uploaded icons
to the Google Playstore and given Google permission

00:07:11.960 --> 00:07:13.130
to use that artwork.

00:07:13.130 --> 00:07:16.890
And their artwork does actually belong to
the people who have created the application.

00:07:16.890 --> 00:07:17.890
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: Very true.

00:07:17.890 --> 00:07:22.810
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: So, to the people that made
AppSales, um, the one thing that I would wanna

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:27.661
be sure of, and of course I have no idea,
but in general you wanna make sure that you

00:07:27.661 --> 00:07:33.470
have negotiated the rights to these icons
before you use them because you don't necessarily

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:35.400
have permission to use them in this context.

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:36.470
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: That's right.

00:07:36.470 --> 00:07:39.950
And in this instance, I imagine it's not gonna
be too hard to get that approval if you're

00:07:39.950 --> 00:07:43.110
able to reach out because you're basically
helping people to sell their apps when they've

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:44.110
got them on sale.

00:07:44.110 --> 00:07:48.920
So it's free advertising, but as Ian said,
just because it is definitely useful for them

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:51.160
doesn't mean that you automatically get the
right to use them.

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:52.160
&gt;&gt;Ian Ni-Lewis: Yep.

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:54.920
&gt;&gt;Reto Meier: The other thing, which I'm gonna
